<poem>
    <metadata>
        <first_line>A Wind that rose</first_line>
        <date period="middle">1873</date>
        <poem_number>J1259</poem_number>
        <source>https://www.edickinson.org/editions/2/image_sets/12172016</source>
        <recipient>T.W. Higginson</recipient>
        <poem_themes>nature, the mind, solitude</poem_themes>
    </metadata>
    
    <body>
        <stanza> 
            <line><nature nature_type="air">A Wind</nature> that rose</line>
            <line>Though not a <nature nature_type="earth">Leaf</nature></line>
            <line>In any <nature nature_type="earth">Forest</nature> stirred</line>
            <line>But with itself did <mind>cold</mind> engage</line> <!-- I have seen interpretations 
                that the "wind" is a metaphor for the mind and thinking, so I am tagging as such -->
            <line>Beyond the Realm of <nature nature_type="animal">Bird</nature><mind/> -</line>
            <!-- the realm beyond that of birds (ie: nature) is the mind -->
            <line>A Wind that woke a <solitude>lone</solitude> <emotion emotion_type="happiness">Delight</emotion></line>
            <line>Like <solitude>Separation's</solitude> Swell</line>
            <line>Restored in Arctic <emotion emotion_type="confidence">Confidence</emotion></line>
            <line>To <mind>the Invisible</mind> -</line>
        </stanza>
    </body>
</poem>

<!-- 
A Wind that rose
Though not a Leaf
In any Forest stirred
But with itself did cold engage
Beyond the Realm of Bird -
A Wind that woke a lone Delight
Like Separation's Swell
Restored in Arctic Confidence
To the Invisible -
-->